Russian communism is making a comeback
Moscow — More than a year ago, while on leave from my teaching position at an American university, I returned to my hometown, Moscow.
My destination was not a stronghold of freedom of speech.
But there was still some freedom left here.
Opposition leader Alexei Navalny traveled across the country in an attempt to gain support from politicians not under the control of the Kremlin.
Protests erupted.
Independent non-governmental organizations operate domestically.
Journalists and analysts do not necessarily follow the Kremlin's line.
The Communist Party is widely seen as a relic of history.
Since then, Navalny has been imprisoned, and his protest movement has been suppressed.
Its anti-corruption foundation was dissolved for "extremism," and its members are being exiled or investigated.
Almost every day, journalists, media outlets, human rights advocates, or independent organizations are added to the "foreign agents" list — even worse — labeled as "undesirable."
In the past year, Russia has been in a non-free state, though not far from it, but very intense.
For example, the law on designating foreign agents was enacted in 2012, aimed at undermining or discrediting organizations or individuals engaged in "political activities" and simultaneously receiving funding from abroad.
But the application of this law has become increasingly arbitrary, to the point where retweeting now can also be a reason for being labeled a foreign agent.
The "undesirable" label can lead to complete prohibition.
) This year alone, a record-breaking 101 entities have been added to the foreign agents list.
The total of 359 includes 88 media-related organizations and individuals.
According to the Russian government, these "agents" must be listed because they "influence national politics."
But the core purpose of journalism and propaganda is certainly to influence politics.
This is precisely the problem: although President Vladimir Putin has positioned himself to continue controlling Russian politics for the foreseeable future, he views criticism as a threat to his survival.
Despite all this silence and persecution, it is an unlikely group—the Communist Party—that has survived and become the only genuine opposition to the Kremlin.
This is largely due to Navalny's "smart voting" strategy—encouraging people to support forces most likely to defeat Kremlin-backed candidates—and the Communist Party performed very strongly in last month's parliamentary and regional elections.
Official data shows that Communist Party candidates won 18.9% of the votes in the State Duma (parliament), while the Kremlin-backed United Russia party received nearly 49.8%.
But the Communists refuse to accept this result, insisting that the voting was manipulated.
In fact, some experts estimate that they should have received about 30% of the votes, while United Russia should have received about 35%.
For many Russians, Communists now seem more respected than Putin.
But they are no longer the Communists of old.
They do not deny the pleasures of the world; instead, party members wear fur coats, enjoy traveling abroad, drive foreign cars, and use social media.
Some are millionaires—such as the charismatic agricultural chief Pavel Gudin, who was banned from participating in last month's elections.
Although the party is still led by the 77-year-old Gennadiy Zyuganov, it is increasingly influenced and supported by younger members.
Taking Nikolay Bondarenko as an example.
The 36-year-old Bondarenko, nicknamed "Red Navalny," severely criticized the poorly designed pension reform of 2018.
Recently, when a regional minister claimed that Russians should be able to "eat better" with as little as 3,500 rubles (about $50) per month, Bondarenko recorded on his YouTube channel his efforts to prove the minister wrong.
Despite being threatened with disqualification, Bondarenko was still allowed to participate in the recent State Duma election.
Although he received support from Navalny's smart voting system, he still lost to the candidate from United Russia.
But his potential should not be overlooked: he recently drafted a protest headline accusing "the state and government" of taking over United Russia.
Then there is 43-year-old Anastasia Yudashova.
Like Bondarev, she astonishingly lost the last election.
But she remains very — and increasingly — popular.
Thanks to the Smart Voting system, another rising star, the elegant Yekaterina Ngaralieva, was elected to the Moscow City Duma in 2019.
Ironically, the modernization of the Communist Party reflects a longing for the past: in 1917, Lenin's Bolsheviks promised justice and equality, and the country that achieved these ideals, though strict, was still not devoid of fairness and compassion.
In addition, like the liberal Navalny, today's Communist Party represents a predictable and consistent vision, under which an individual's eccentricity does not affect everyone.
It is precisely based on this logic that all opponents of the Kremlin are increasingly uniting: forming a "United Russia" that can challenge United Russia.
This situation is not limited to Russia alone.
In the recent parliamentary elections in the Czech Republic, Andrej Babiš — also known as Czech Donald Trump — failed to be re-elected as prime minister, as opposition alliances set aside their ideological differences and formed a common coalition, with leader Petr Fiala very likely to lead the new government together with another opposition alliance.
As Fiala said, "People are tired of populists," and they want "normal, competent, and decent politics."
The opposition in Hungary will also prepare a unified election list for next year's parliamentary elections and send a single candidate to run for prime minister.
Of course, the Czech Republic still maintains a democratic system, so Babiš is preparing to join the opposition forces.
Meanwhile, toppling Putin is far more difficult, and it is not hard to predict more measures aimed at crushing the Communist Party will follow.
But this approach also brings risks to the Kremlin.
Currently, the president claims that Russian democracy "has not died," and points to the country still having "an active opposition" as evidence, which shows he at least still has an interest in pretending that Russia is not being led toward near-authoritarianism.
Putin says he only wants stability.
But his regime is pushing Russia toward a more turbulent situation.
If the Kremlin, like it did with Russia's liberals, inconsistently makes and enforces rules, driving the Communist Party underground, social explosion is even more likely to occur.
And if it decides no longer to suppress them, the Communist Party of Russia—yes, the Communists—could become an undeniable force.
